Dorsal, anal and caudal fins with very small dark spots on interradial membranes. Very small dark spots present also on the bases of some body scales in adult specimens. In juveniles the spotted pattern of the body is much more pronounced, with virtually every scale on the body having a dark spot at its base, including those in the anterior part of the E 4 scale row (i.e. as in adult
A. scitulus
). Juveniles, on the contrary, without spots in unpaired fins.

Distribution. Australoheros kaaygua
has a disjunct distribution, including tributaries of the Río Iguazú, a tributary of Río Paraná in Brazil and Argentina (
Casciotta, Almirón and Gómez, 2006
), and tributaries of the Upper Rio Uruguay in Brazil (
Fig. 14
).
